An ice-out assessment was conducted on Big Birch Lake in 2013 to evaluate the Northern Pike population. A Northern Pike experimental regulation requiring the release of all pike over 24 inches was implemented in 1996. The regulation was later modified in 2006 to a protected slot between 24 and 36 inches with one fish over 36 inches allowed in possession. The regulation is up for review in March of 2015 and a decision will be made to either drop the regulation or make it permanent.
The ice-out assessment included setting early nets in Fish Creek and near the inlet from a small marsh on the south side of Big Birch Lake to intercept spawning pike. Attempts were made to set additional trap nets in the lake when access to open areas was possible. Late ice melt and shifting ice in the lake allowed only ten trap nets to be set in a one week period. The late, cooler spring and low stream flows likely had a negative effect on pike catches in both stream and lake trap nets.
All Northern Pike, Walleye, Largemouth Bass, Black Crappie, and most of the Bluegill were measured. Other fish species were identified and counted. Scales were taken from male and female Northern Pike to compare age classes and growth rates between the sexes. A partial fin-clip was given to the left anal fin to keep track of recaptures. Recaptured fish were noted but not re-measured. Seven females and sixteen males were recaptured in the stream sets. All pike in the lake nets were new fish although one was a fish marked from a previous ice-out assessment.
A total of 458 Northern Pike were netted with the two gear types in the 2013 ice-out assessment. Ice-out assessments were also conducted in 2010, odd years between 2001 and 2009, and five years between 1993 and 1998. Not all of the ice-out assessments were conducted with the same gear types. A table included at the end of the report shows the results from all ice-out assessments. After the 2010 ice-out assessment, there appeared to be an improvement in the proportion of fish exceeding thirty inches in length, however, the percentage declined in 2013 and resembled results from the 2009 assessment.
Ages 2 through 10 were represented in the female portion of the 2013 ice-out assessment and ages 1 through 8 in the male portion. The abundant year classes suggest consistent recruitment. A strong year class from 2009 accounted for 31% of the combined catch. Prior to implementation of the regulation few Northern Pike were documented beyond 6 years of age. Age 1 males displayed fast growth while the remaining age groups of both sexes showed normal growth when compared to an Area Mean Back-calculated Length table. Females grew from 2.6 to 5.8 inches longer than males of the same age.
The small sample sizes for Northern Pike gathered in ice-out assessments prior to the regulation implementation (1996) may not have provided a reliably accurate representation of past pike populations. Extensive ice-out netting completed since 1998 has not shown a trend of steadily increasing mean length, mean weight, % of fish over 24 inches, or % of females over 30 inches. There does appear to be more Northern Pike exceeding thirty inches than were present before the regulation.
Lake trap nets in previous assessments typically were more effective than the stream nets at catching a sample size with a longer mean length and heavier mean weight. With the late ice-out in 2013, the majority of pike likely spawned under the ice and did not frequent the shoal waters during the netting period. In the 2013 assessment, more and larger female pike were netted in the stream nets. Seventy-five of the pike from the stream sample were females greater than 24 inches in length compared to only six females in the lake nets. In the 2010 pike assessment when comparing the same type of nets, seventy-two females exceeding twenty-four inches were caught in the lake trap nets while forty-one females were in the stream nets.
Some of the previous ice-out assessments have also been used to provide data on the Walleye population in Big Birch Lake. The lake nets were usually moved to rocky substrates or open sand favored by spawning Walleye later in the assessments and large-frame trap nets were also incorporated. The ice-out assessments in 2010 and 2007 targeted both Northern Pike and Walleye and used standard lake survey trap nets as well as large-frame trap nets. Catches of 219 and 262 Walleye were recorded in 2010 and 2007, respectively. Fewer Walleye (n=32) were sampled in the 2013 assessment as Northern Pike was the target species.
Smaller Walleye comprised a greater proportion of the 2013 sample than in previous assessments. The largest Walleye in 2013 was only 23.2 inches compared to maximum lengths of 27.5 to 30.3 inches in prior assessments. This was likely due to the late ice-out and the majority of the female Walleyes having finished spawning.
Other fish species sampled in the 2013 ice-out assessment included eight Largemouth Bass between 10.2 and 17.8 inches in length as well as fifty Black Crappie from 5.8 to 13 inches in length. Twenty-eight Bluegill up to 8.7 inches were sampled in the lake trap nets. Bowfin, Brown Bullhead, Green Sunfish, hybrid sunfish, Pumpkinseed, Rock Bass, and Yellow Perch were also sampled.

An ice-out assessment was conducted on Big Birch Lake in 2014 to evaluate the Northern Pike population. A Northern Pike experimental regulation requiring the release of all pike over 24 inches was implemented in 1996. The regulation was later modified in 2006 to a protected slot between 24 and 36 inches with one fish over 36 inches allowed in possession. The regulation was up for review in March of 2015 and a decision was made to drop the regulation. Public meetings held in September of 2014 to gage feelings about the regulation showed mostly opposition.
Netting pike proved to be a challenge again on Big Birch Lake with low stream flows, cooler weather, high winds, and delayed ice-out. The majority of Northern Pike caught came from Fish Creek (58%; n=260) as that was the first location to open up. This net was set and pulled several times to spread out the catch which was a strategy not used in previous assessments. The Fish Creek location has typically provided a high pike catch which has been dominated by smaller fish. An additional inlet on the south shore has traditionally been sampled prior to ice-out with a trap net with two leads set at the mouth. This set has tended to capture more large pike.
The 2014 ice-out assessment included setting early nets in Fish Creek, near the inlet from a small marsh on the south side of Big Birch Lake, and the inlet from Bass Lake on the north shore to intercept spawning pike. Attempts were made to set additional trap nets in the lake when access to open areas was possible. Changing temperatures and strong winds dictated lake net set dates and locations. There was a 20 day difference between when the first net was set at Fish Creek and the first net set in the lake. By the time the lake nets were set, most of the female pike were ripe or spent indicating the primary spawning period was complete which is typical with late ice-out. Only 42 of the pike caught came from the lake sets.
All Northern Pike, Walleye, Largemouth Bass, Black Crappie, and most of the Bluegill were measured. Other fish species were identified and counted. Scales were taken from Walleye to compare age classes and growth rates between the sexes. Northern Pike scales were not taken as a sufficient number could be collected from the summer gill nets. A partial fin clip was given to the pike to keep track of recaptures. Recaptured fish were noted but not re-measured. Two female and four male pike were recaptured during the netting period. Several marked pike from a previous ice-out assessment were also caught in one of the lake nets.
A total of 451 Northern Pike were netted in the 2014 ice-out assessment. Ice-out assessments were also conducted in 2013, 2010, odd years between 2001 and 2009, and five years between 1993 and 1998. Not all of the ice-out assessments were conducted with the same gear types. A table included at the end of the report shows the results from all ice-out assessments. After the 2010 ice-out assessment, there appeared to be an improvement in the proportion of fish exceeding 30 inches in length, however, the percentage declined in 2013 and resembled results from the 2009 assessment. The recent results were comparable to those from 2013.
The small sample sizes for Northern Pike caught in ice-out assessments prior to the regulation implementation (1996) may not have provided a reliably accurate representation of past pike populations. Extensive ice-out netting completed since 1998 has not shown a trend of steadily increasing mean length, mean weight, % of fish over 24 inches, or % of females over 30 inches. Through statistical analysis (Dave Staples, May, 2014) there does, however, appear to be more Northern Pike exceeding 30 inches than were present before the regulation.
Lake trap nets in previous assessments typically were more effective than the stream nets at catching a sample size with a longer mean length and heavier mean weight. With the late ice-out conditions in both 2014 and 2013, the majority of pike likely spawned under the ice and did not frequent the shoal waters during the netting period. In both assessments, more and larger female pike were netted in the stream nets. Forty of the pike from Fish Creek and forty from the two early inlet sets were females which exceeded 24 inches in length. The longest pike was 35.8 inches which came from the early inlet set on the south shore. Only 10 of the pike caught in lake trap nets were longer than 24 inches. In 2013, 75 pike from the stream sample were females greater than 24 inches in length compared to only six females in the lake nets. In the 2010 pike assessment when comparing the same gear types, 72 females exceeding 24 inches were caught in the lake trap nets compared to 41 females in stream nets. (See Table 1: Northern Pike  Big Birch Lake)
Some of the previous ice-out assessments were also used to provide data on the Walleye population in Big Birch Lake. The lake nets were usually moved to rocky substrates or open sand favored by spawning Walleye later in the assessments and large-frame trap nets were also incorporated. Walleye were not a target species in 2014, although length measurements and scales were taken to supplement age data from the 2014 summer survey. A total of 30 Walleye were caught that measured from 17.9 to 27.9 inches in length. Fewer Walleye (n=32) were also sampled in the 2013 assessment as Northern Pike was the target species. Catches of 219 and 262 walleye were recorded in 2010 and 2007, respectively.
Ages six, nine, and twelve were represented in the female Walleye sample and five through eight, and fifteen in the male portion. Most of the fish in both samples, 85% of females, and 65% of males, came from the 2008 year class which corresponds to a fry stocked year. Female Walleye showed normal to fast growth while males showed normal to slow growth rates when compared to an Area Mean Back-calculated Length table.
Other fish species sampled in the 2014 ice-out assessment included six Largemouth Bass between 6.0 and 15.6 inches in length as well as twelve Black Crappie from 5.9 to 11.5 inches in length. Eighteen Bluegill up to 7.8 inches were sampled in the lake trap nets. Bowfin, Brown Bullhead, hybrid sunfish, Pumpkinseed, Rock Bass, and White Sucker were also caught.
Recent ice-out assessments have suggested that there has been an improvement in the number of Northern Pike exceeding 30 inches, but catch results have not met the management goals of the experimental regulation. Following public meetings and comment period, there was little support for the regulation and the recommendation was to drop the regulation in the 2015 fishing season.

Big Birch Lake (DOW# 77-0084; Lake Class 22) is a 2,112-acre lake located near Grey Eagle, Minnesota. There are five Minnesota Department of Natural Resources (MNDNR) owned boat ramps located around the lake. Big Birch Lake has 15.26 miles of shoreline and a maximum depth of 81 feet. The lake is primarily managed for Walleye and Northern Pike and secondarily for Bluegill, Largemouth Bass, and Smallmouth Bass. The lake was initially surveyed in 1981 and 40 fish sampling surveys or investigations have occurred since then with the most recent prior sampling in 2016 (targeted survey for young of year Walleye). Fall night electrofishing has be completed on an annual or biennial basis since 1994 in Big Birch Lake.

One hour of fall night electrofishing was conducted on Big Birch to evaluate success of annual alternate rate (1,500 fry/LA & 3,000 fry/LA) fry stocking. The young of year (YOY) Walleye catch rate was 5.0 fish per hour. This was lower than in 2016 (16.0 fish per hour), and continued a 4 year decline in YOY catch rates. Mean length of YOY Walleye was 6.20 inches. This was smaller than in 2016 (7.15 inches), but was similar to past surveys.
